    <title>Combined summary - Lock protocol version numbers</title>
    <updated>2023-06-04T21:08:59.518964+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2011-November/000715.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin-development mailing list has been discussing various ideas for naming conventions and client identification. One proposal is to lock version numbers to the protocol version, while using the sub_version_num field and revision number for individual builds, in order to avoid version bumping insanity. Some members suggested using user-agent strings, but others argued that it could lead to developers making communication choices based on client types. However, there were also arguments that user-agent strings can be necessary and valuable in dealing with bugs.A hierarchy was proposed for user-agent strings, starting from protocol, variant, GUI, flavour, and build. The importance of strict adherence to the protocol and rejecting non-compliant clients was emphasized. The consensus was that adherence to the protocol is critical, and clear and concise definition of the protocol, and strict adherence in the mainline client, are the best options available.Another discussion revolved around the use of the sub_version_num field in identifying client and version of Bitcoin. While some supported using user-agent strings to identify clients, others preferred a simple string without any further meaning. It was agreed that adherence to the protocol is critical, and clients that do not comply should be rejected outright. The use of the sub_version_num field as a Client and Version identifier was proposed, with a suggestion that IDENTIFIER VERSION is a format clients can follow, while allowing them to define the field however they wish. A BIP was suggested to formalize how this information will be included and used to encourage more supporters to the scene.The Bitcoin community discussed the protocol version numbers and client identifiers, with suggestions for a unique name such as "Satoshi" as an identifier. There were suggestions for creating a BIP to define guidelines for client and version identifiers, acknowledging that different projects would have different release scheduling schemes. The group agreed that it is important to adhere to the protocol and reject non-compliant clients, while also considering the potential benefits and drawbacks of using user-agent strings.</summary>
